What is CAP Theorem?

CAP Theorem is about distributed systems—systems where your data is spread across many computers (nodes). It says:

You can’t have Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance all at the same time—at least during a network problem.

Let’s define them in plain terms:

Consistency (C) → Everyone sees the same latest data. If you update something, all nodes know it immediately. No one sees old/stale info.
Example: Bank balance must always be accurate.
Availability (A) → The system always gives you a response, even if some nodes are out-of-date.
Example: Social media feed still loads even if some servers are down.
Partition Tolerance (P) → The system keeps working even if network fails and nodes can’t talk to each other.
Example: Some servers in another city can’t connect, but the system doesn’t crash.

Key idea:
When the network splits (partition), you must choose:

Consistency → Some users may see errors or timeouts, but data is always correct.
Availability → Everyone gets a response, but some data may be temporarily wrong.
CP vs AP: Two Ways to Handle Failures

1. CP (Consistency + Partition Tolerance)

Focus: Data is always correct.
Behavior: If the network splits, the side with fewer nodes may stop working.
Example: Bank system refuses a transaction if it can’t be sure balance is correct.
Pros: No conflicting data.
Cons: Some requests fail during partition.

2. AP (Availability + Partition Tolerance)

Focus: System stays up at all costs.
Behavior: Both sides of a split keep working, even if data may be inconsistent temporarily.
Example: Social media feeds continue showing posts, even if some servers have slightly old data.
Pros: System is always available.
Cons: Some data may need fixing later (eventual consistency).
How a Partition Actually Plays Out

Imagine 5 servers:

Network splits → 3 servers on one side, 2 on the other.

CP system:

Majority (3 nodes) keeps working.
Minority (2 nodes) stops processing writes.
When network heals → minority updates from majority. ✅ Correct data, some users saw errors.

AP system:

Both sides keep accepting writes.
When network heals → system resolves conflicts. ⚠️ Some users saw slightly inconsistent data.
Common Mistakes People Make
Thinking CAP is permanent → Systems aren’t “always CP or AP.” Normal operation can give both.
Ignoring partition tolerance → Network failures will happen; you can’t avoid them.
Confusing CAP consistency with ACID consistency → CAP is about distributed nodes, ACID is about transactions inside a database.
Forgetting recovery → Choosing availability requires a plan to fix conflicts later.
How to Decide: A Simple Question

What hurts more: returning wrong data, or returning no data?

Wrong data hurts → Pick CP (e.g., payments, bank balances).
No data hurts → Pick AP (e.g., feeds, search, analytics).

Most real systems mix them:

CP core → Handles critical, correct data.
AP edges → Serve cached or fast-access data to users.
Takeaway

CAP doesn’t give new options—it tells you what your system is already doing during failures and whether it’s the right tradeoff.

In short: CAP is about making conscious choices for network failures, not about limiting your system forever.
